Legal Calculus 4.5 — Enhanced Modules — Module 25
📘 Legal Calculus — Module 25

Privilege Logs — Clawback & Inadvertent Production

⚖️ Core Message

Protect privilege without obstructing discovery: log, claw back, and move on.
📖 Lesson Content

1. Provide logs with date, author/recipient, type, and basis (attorney‑client/work product).
2. Use a FRE 502(d) clawback order to reduce disputes.
3. Segregate partial redactions from full withholdings.
4. Update logs promptly as productions roll.
📝 Assignment

Draft a one‑page sample privilege log (5 entries) and a short 502(d) proposed order.
✅ Model Response

PRIVILEGE LOG (excerpt)

No. 3 | 7/29/25 | Email | Atty Smith → Clerk | Work product | Redacted

 

[PROPOSED] 502(d) ORDER: Inadvertent disclosure shall not waive privilege;

producing party may claw back upon notice.

 

💡 Reflection Summary

Clarity reduces fights; 502(d) ends many of them.
🎨 Visual Concept

A ledger with two columns: Redacted / Withheld, stamped 502(d).
